Health & Finance Data Analysis
Project
A real-world style data science project exploring how financial
factors
(income, savings, insurance premiums) relate to health outcomes
and costs
(BMI, smoking, medical expenses).
What this project does
1. Loads data — uses a realistic synthetic dataset by default, or
your
own CSV if you provide one.
2. Explores the data — summary stats and correlations between
financial
and health variables.
3. Visualizes insights — 4 charts saved to
health_finance_insights.png :
Income vs medical expenses (by smoker status)
Healthcare cost as % of income: smoker vs non-smoker
BMI vs insurance premium
Distribution of healthcare cost burden
4. Builds predictive models — Linear Regression and Random
Forest to
predict medical expenses from health + financial features,
with
accuracy metrics (MAE, R²) and feature importance ranking.Files
File Purpose
health_finance_analysis.py Main script — run this
health_finance_insights.png
Generated after running
(charts)
Setup
pip install pandas numpy matplotlib seaborn scikitlearn
Run
python health_finance_analysis.py
This prints dataset stats, correlations, model performance, and
feature
importance to the console, and saves the chart image.
Using your own data
Replace the load_data() call at the bottom of the script:
data = load_data(csv_path="your_file.csv")
Your CSV should have these columns (rename to match if neededage, sex, bmi, children, smoker, region,
annual_income, savings, insurance_premium,
medical_expenses
A great real dataset to try: the classic Kaggle "Medical Cost
Personal
Datasets" ( insurance.csv ) — just add annual_income and
savings
columns from another source, or simulate them, since that dataset
doesn't
include income data natively.
Key columns explained
annual_income — yearly household income
savings — estimated savings, penalized by smoking/high BMI
in the
synthetic generator
insurance_premium — annual cost of health insurance
medical_expenses — actual healthcare spending (the
prediction target)
health_cost_ratio (derived) — (medical expenses + premium) /
income,
a measure of financial burden from healthcare
Possible extensions
Add time-series data to track costs/savings over multiple
years
Cluster households into financial-health risk segments
(KMeans)
Add a Streamlit dashboard for interactive exploration
Bring in real regional cost-of-living or insurance market data
